The first virtual provider will come to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech suppliers offer virtually all services as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, there is something missing here - a virtual provider who forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe this one won't wait long.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that the Czech mobile service providers are working on the most expensive in Europe at all.
This also confirmed by the Telecommunications Authority ČT, which pointed out that the price for a SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the area of regulation of roaming charges, it is likely that there is a paradoxical situation - SMS from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of the Czech mobile service providers than home.
Why are prices in the Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a battle statement.
Perhaps it sounds paradox, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile telephony providers are happy to hamper on the fact that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority Pavel Dvořák, who had often expressed in the past that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with its own network will no longer have very many opportunities (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual providers to the mobile market that led to a significant price reduction, which the classical mobile operators had to respond to.
Before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the UK market, there were similar voices as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don't have to look for examples long.
In February we reported about the start of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just a half year, this provider managed to gain more than 100 thousand customers and thus to become the fifth largest provider in the country.
The financial group Penta, which owns, among other things, U: fon in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual providers is to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually prosper themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, but often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be quite a good chess to set on a non-cliché target group.
This provider is specifically targeted at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider that they like and who they can trust," said David Seibert, the CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar approach as in Poland could take foot in the Czech Republic as well.
The press spokesman of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services. "
In Czechoslovakia, the mobile telephony providers mean
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile service provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile king.
"Although we are talking about an expansion of this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look particularly hopeful.
Mobilking will be more likely to enter the market in other countries of our region, "says a telephone call for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, press lecturer of the financial group Penta.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile telephony providers in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to do so.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
Their interest in launching a virtual mobile service provider has for a long time shown the GTS Novera group, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network services but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have negotiated this possibility repeatedly with all Czech mobile telephony providers.
With some of them, we have already been able to achieve negotiation progress, "said the press spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Non-official information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an inescapable wall of silence.
"At this moment we do not assume that there is room for a full virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has a wide range of features compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area, "says his explanation for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeç from the press department of Telefónica O2.
The specification of the Czech market also points to other suppliers.
The press preacher of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds rarely to the statement of O2: "We have not yet found a viable and both sides of the project that could be built on."
And it adds: "In the network of T-Mobile will hardly show up a virtual provider by the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have a concrete offer to think in the short term. "
Vodafone focuses more on fulfilling the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
This is exactly what we regard as the best from the point of view of our customers.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area lies in the search for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet. "
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
The behaviour of mobile broadcasters is easy to understand, another provider was called more competition, this would lead to decreasing prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
So why should such a competitor be facilitated to enter the market?
The fact that the suppliers can draw on a string when it comes to something also demonstrates the long way back and forth around the emergence of U: fon.
The most likely pressure in the direction of ČT was at the moment, when U: fon came to the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This also demonstrates the information available to the public from the ČT web pages.
Now, however, you are right: fon as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová said: "The field of competition of the mobile communications market was also recently strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile service provider.
Taking into account the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that a new operator would make high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services. "
However, in view of this approach by the mobile broadcasters, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
It is not only about the attitude of ČT which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic - unlike the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
It is exclusively owned by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, referred to this whole problem's very typical attitude.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile service provider would be possible after a contract between a mobile service provider and a virtual provider has been concluded through the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic suppliers, "so in his reply to our question Kristián Chalupa from the ÚOHS External Relations Department.
Representatives of the suppliers would not surprise such a wording.
This is more than worrying by an authority that represents consumer interests and, among other things, is to ensure that no one misuses its position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In abroad, where virtual providers work perfectly normally, it is to be observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not one of the interests of ÚOHS.
It is really shocking in this case that the three mobile telephony providers are almost already touching together, resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolute same gas price at the gas stations is certainly only a coincidence and the result of a tough competition.
"The Authority has not detected any evidence in this case indicating any action directed against competition, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the suppliers have a dominant position on the market, so they do not have the appropriate increased responsibility for acting on the market.
The necessary instruments for opening the mobile market to virtual providers are likely to be missing also by the Telecommunications Regulatory Authority, "said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by ČT, after which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile broadcasters have a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - for the entry of a virtual provider to the market, the approval of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile telephony provider has the monopoly for its network - logical - for its network.
This means that it necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if you do not agree with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile broadcasters are acting alike.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the above-mentioned company GTS Novera) show that they face very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The deflection of responsibility to the ČT is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances from the whole matter.
This was already observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the newly adopted Novelle of the Telecommunications Act failed to enforce the extension of the competences of ČT to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS need to know that too well, but they probably have different interests.
It's okay if no one looks
The functioning of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are more than one in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
It is companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but they are only partially public.
They are usually companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Own mobile telephone services, for example, offer Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only come to selected ones.
The joke of the case is that the company acts as a classic company customer compared to the operator who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a major customer, he will receive special offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile service providers prohibit a similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which may lead to an end to cooperation with the relevant society," Martina Kemrová replied to our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing does not speak around the responsibility of the mobile service providers.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, it may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator is opposed to such an approach.
In fact, they do not have negligible profits from the activities of these companies, at the same time, in contrast to the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite all, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card does not run on their phone's name, so they cannot have full access to it like the normal customers of the mobile service providers. "
But that alone should be the least strange thing for the ČT.
In addition, another question opens up for the ÚOHS.
Do mobile telephony providers face up to such an approach, why are they blocking themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want it, it does not have to satisfy itself with the statement by the suppliers that they do not know about it and their business conditions would prohibit it.
When Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has been emphasised several times in the text, the entry of virtual providers into the market led to a significant fall in the price of the various services.
In practice, in all countries where virtual providers have been created, classical suppliers have tried to prevent their emergence practically more or less.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - a too small or too much saturated market, problems in the quality of services, etc.
However, in the highly developed countries, the regulatory bodies have just intervened in these moments, which did not attempt to protect the interests of mobile service providers but their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing up the whole case like a hot potato.
On the basis of our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclarity in competences in these cases is more than favourable.
But let's not throw the curtain into the grain.
If the background information is correct and soon a virtual provider appears, the Czech mobile market may soon be moving again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting other interested parties (to discriminate against them).
And the Czechs will finally not make more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
