Drivers who can be reversed due to alcohol levels will have to install the 'alcolock'.
The authority orders that the driver who had three official penalties for the alcohol level installed this system in his car, which forbids him to start the car in drunk condition. If he is alcoholized, then the car will not start.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is now part of the report of the prosecutor-general. According to her, it is a pilot project that will last for a year.
The purpose is to rehabilitate the driver, which is why he receives a course for the retraining of transport behaviour.
In addition to the Attorney General, the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for the Safety of Automobiles will participate in this process.
According to statistics, between 30-75% of the drivers who were displayed more than once due to driving under alcohol flow, returned to tax.
The 'alcolock' would prevent this because it is connected to a system connected to the car, it measures the alcoholic content in the breathed air and prevents car start when the driver has done an alcohol test; or if an alcohol concentration is detected that is higher than permitted.
It costs more than 1 000 euros, the costs are borne by the person who imposes the penalty.
In this context, a study carried out in the USA in 2007 has shown that cars equipped with these devices already prevent up to 65% of the regulatory infringements in the first year following its introduction.
In Spain, it is expected that 115 lives could be saved every year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to tackle this behaviour before it becomes a crime.
And in order to facilitate their implementation, legislative reform can be implemented by the ordinary way, and yet a reform of the basic law is required which is necessary for the law enforcement process.
The equipment is still not available in any business in the Spanish markets, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
The House of Members will vote tomorrow because of the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses, which has already been done in France.
