Discussion - From the blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of her foundation, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to be pleased because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it recovered the public's trust, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of infected blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves managed by the blood donation service of the Canadian Red Cross during the 1980s were contaminated with HI virus and hepatitis C virus.
In view of this tragedy and the dissatisfaction of the public, the Government of Canada launched in February 1994 a public investigation initiated by Judge Horace Krever to bring light to the circumstances that had led to such tragedy and to draw up guidelines to prevent a new disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitating to submit his report, several provinces then put a committee on the legs whose aim was to develop a new system for the management of blood preserves in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee completed this mission.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
'1998, when Hema-Quebec started her work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood preservation system in Quebec, remember Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood preserves and through the work in this field over the following years, we have recovered public confidence ', she says, before she is proud to stress that in early 2008, almost 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary retains consciousness that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its creation on 28 September 1998 Hema-Quebec has acted in accordance with the principle of caution.
At this time we experienced the emergence of numerous cases of human form of bovine insanity in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman who has been in charge since the foundation of 1998.
'And we didn't have any idea if this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we referred to one of the main guidelines of the reports by Krever and Gélineau, according to which exclusion measures are applied if you do not know this and if a disease is only progressing slowly, as is apparently the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, there was no doubt that this disease was transmitted over the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied has quite a sense.
In 1999, a much more precise HIV detection technique appeared on the market: Nucleic acid tests (NST) that enable the presence of the virus itself to be demonstrated directly in the donor's blood, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case in the tests used so far.
The NST enabled to reduce the incubation time that takes place between the time when the person was infected and when the first viruses can be demonstrated by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than one week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing, and one could not recognise this was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Nowadays, one in 12 million people is at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
'In other words, this means that you have to distribute 12 million blood preserves before someone gets HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood preserves every year, it would take more than 24 years before a case occurs where HIV was transferred through a blood preserve.
I think you can feel comfortable today when you get a blood transfusion or prescribe it to restore health, "says Hema-Quebec's chief of directors.
'Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can get into the system.
Only last year on the island of Réunion has the Chikungunya virus emerged, which, as well as the Westnil virus, is transmitted through insects through the blood.
We need to monitor continuously ', Dr. Décary continues, before she stresses that Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate supplies in addition to a safe supply.
'The need is increasing because the population is ageing.
As cancer control treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has an impact on the blood donor network, which on average accounts for only 3% of Quebecs population suitable for blood donation. '
In doing so, every healthy person who is 18 years or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of the people who provide their blood are not accepted because, for example, they are infected with AIDS or malaria, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria has spread are excluded from blood donation for a year.
'With these 3% we can get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It's hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep them and make them become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find time to spend an hour donating blood, 'regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Hema-Quebec delivers not only blood preserves, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used in severe burns.
These tissues are investigated, processed and frozen before being deposited at Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public Nabelschnurblutbank Quebecs.
In the umbrella, which was previously considered as biomedical waste, there is rich blood in stem cells that can serve to treat serious diseases such as leukaemia.
'A few weeks ago we celebrated the deployment of our thousands of navels' blood sample, and we plan to decrease more than a thousand a year.
"We should probably start making it available for transplants at the beginning of next year," Dr. Décary further explains which describes this program of navel cuttings as very popular.
'Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it 'because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all hospitals Quebecs.
