This confirms, and pursues an orthodox logic, that the world's largest gold-winning company sought an assault against three authors and a small medieval publisher, with the aim of opening a 'public transparent debate'.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge about the truth, especially not in the case of envy lawsuits, but about the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference has been completely concealed by Mr Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to represent one of their opposed opinions.
No matter how the process goes, the authors and the publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defence and fight with very uneven weapons against an army of lawyers paid out of the almost inexhaustible bags of the gold mine.
Tactic in these unequal struggles is, moreover, often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensual arrangement that makes the opposite dead and, moreover, scares off anyone who dares to deal with the question again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she should have presented her view of things in front of the public opinion.
Contrary to what has been done in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates are usually carried out in Canada through the exchange of ideas and not through clubs.
So it would have been enough if the gold mine had published its books and files and opened a real debate through the newspapers, media, publications and the financing of independent audit teams that could have brought light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and wipes aside the petitions and letters to support the authors of Noir Canada with a hand movement.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he can ask for a 'public' debate at the same time, while ignoring the views of this public?
It seems that this word in the world of the Vice-President only includes the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a very narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, self-destitute has the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public who supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does this especially because it rejects the brutal attitude of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a troublesome lawsuit (during the 'public debate' Barrick Gold has just made a claim to the authors of Noir Canada, in which it asks them not to use this term anymore...).
Apart from the surreal speech by Mr Garver, the Barrick Gold complaint is a direct attack on freedom to academic research and the truth finding which is fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to quote credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to explore and discuss issues that do not like the rich companies of the world, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could lead it by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong for a long time has been able to deal with debates and disagreements and to resolve conflicts.
The disproportionate complaint by Barrick Gold clearly shows that, unlike what she claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate, and it is time for governments to take measures that restrict this kind of unjustified actions.
Rescue action for the Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans understand
The Bush administration and the senior congressmen, Republicans and Democrats have finally reached agreement yesterday on the most extensive economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 30s.
The new version of the plan of over $700 billion to stop the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months still needs to be accepted by the two congress chambers.
The main contents are: better control of Members of Parliament over the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of the public funds used, new resources to reduce the number of houses arrested due to residual payments, as well as the right to monitor the salaries paid to the managers of the supported companies.
The American financial secretary Henry Paulson, the President of the Nancy Pelosi Chamber of Representatives, and the representative of the Republicans, Senator Judd Gregg, announced yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, the good news, after a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be market-effective," said Bush's representative, Henry Paulson.
"Everything happened to protect the real economy and the American people from the crisis on Wall Street," said the Democrat.
'This is the fundamental point: If we do not, the trauma, chaos and unrest in the daily life of the Americans will be enormous, 'said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had accelerated over the last two hours, for fear of the impact that a new failure would have had on the mood of investors.
The deadline that had been agreed was the opening of the market this morning.
The two American presidential candidates who only took part late in the negotiations showed themselves to be more supportive of the agreement but did not fail to express their dissatisfaction about the need to meet them in this extreme way.
The democratic Senator Barrack Obama insisted on the addition of certain consent to agreement, in particular those which should enable owners to keep their houses, and those that concern the salaries of the senior employees of the companies rescued by the State.
'If you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the lack of responsibility of certain people, that is nothing you could congratulate yourself on.
But these measures are necessary ', he explained on the American television broadcasters.
When he was asked on another station whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied: 'I would like to know the details first, but I hope so.
'The guideline I have read shows that this is one thing that we will all have to digest, and that we will be able to move forward with.
The option to do nothing is simply not acceptable ', he said.
The $700 billion plan is aimed at using the money of taxpayers
