The psychology of the surrender - or why we are willing to pay more
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overestimate the error offered.
Neurologers and economists at the University of New York have now managed to discover the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and apparently irrational behaviour.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to give themselves into a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even too high prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play lotto while the other participated in one playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the volunteers were examined using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the Striatum, a complex below the brains, was measured in the losers of the auction, where the exaggeration of the opponent plays an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-rewarding" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore considered that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the strip.
In order to underpin their thesis, economists in the research group have recruited additional research into the pursuit of money.
In this case, three groups should participate against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product and then made their efforts.
Another group was also promised $15 reward, in case they came out of the game as a winner.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was only that the emphasis on one was on winning, while on the other was on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by Neurologen, the members of the "against losing" group were willing to make higher efforts than those in the control / profit group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
In fact, the behaviour observed at auctions so far has only been justified by the joy of gaining or avoiding risks.
The contradiction between these two theories was dissolved thanks to the imaging neurological processes, so we now have a third statement ready "- said Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Economics Faculty of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to visit the doctor?
In the world, around half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated to be hundreds of thousands in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective concept of infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and yellowing are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ.
Depending on pathogens, hepatitis B, C and D, the virus can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, digestion secret or spicy).
In any case, travellers are recommended to vaccinate against viruses A and B, there is no vaccine against virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A are shown approximately two to three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and fracture.
After that, the yellowish occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and recovery can take up to two-three weeks.
About 1 million people die of hepatitis B every year, far more severe diseases such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that estimates suggest that only every ten infected person is in drug-free treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: untreated may lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen destroys the liver cells homely - in many cases the first symptoms show after 20-30 years.
Therefore, temporary prevention, such as regular checks, is indispensable.
There are three groups where this disease occurs more frequently: those who had undergone a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the physician at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recently recognized, the disease is healing, the virus can be eradicated, causing the risk of infection and preventing the emergence of cancer.
The 30th of September is the World Day of Hepatitis, for the first time organised in 2004 by patients' representations worldwide.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of these chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their emergence and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
As recent research results show that religious faith seems like a kind of "painkillers," which should have already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have carried out an interesting experiment: it was examined how faith in God influenced the sense of pain of man, reported the British magazine "Telegraph."
In the rather bizarre investigation, 12 faithful and athlests each received electric shocks, while they studied a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the faithful were able to eliminate most of the pain.
With a brain scanning technology, it was even demonstrated that the Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that was responsible for pain control.
The study was the first in a research project in which, alongside scientists, philosopher and theologists from different departments of the university also participate.
During the test, the subjects were tied to the left hand of the electric shock.
The participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: one picture of God's mother, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and another Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Hermelin."
The researchers hoped that the face of the Virgin Mary among the faithful would create a kind of religious trance, while she chose da Vinci's image because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt reassuring.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in a MRI scanner, and at this time received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages, while they should either look at the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they felt "safe" at the sight of the Mother of God, as if they were "cared" and they felt "peace and peace."
During the consideration of the religious painting they reported over 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo's work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also took part in the attempt, said that you could also produce similar effects with other, highly active images even among the athlests, you just need to find the corresponding photo.
"We need to find a picture that triggers very positive feelings, such as a mother or a father," says the psychologist.
The Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of research.
"Practicing faith should change our personality, and also in many cases," says Wright.
According to these excellent results, only the question remains what effect a Madonna picture Leonardos or another comparable painter would have on the pain regulation of the faithful.
Would the high-quality Virgin Maria achieve even better results?
