What would be the best method for developing new accident prevention technologies if not to imitate the barrier sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At the CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented in which the Nissan engineers of lobsters were inspired in the creation of new accident avoidance systems.
In cooperation with Tokyo University Nissan has built the biomimetic system of the type BR23C controlled by autobotters, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In the flight each bee forms its own, oval "private area," which is very similar to our own "protective shield," said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can be seen in every direction and in an angle of more than 300 degrees, plays an important role.
In order to imitate the function of the composite eye, researchers seized the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles before the BR23C in a face field of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is recorded in second fractions, and the autobutter immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of bees, by turning the tyres around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this manoeuvre takes place in an instinct manner.
"If it were not, the autopilot could not respond quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, Head of the Mobility Laboratory and the autopilot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most inner and vulnerable part of the shield - a layer that is currently considered inevitable within the accident.
The whole process must reflect the behaviour of bees when they avoid other bees.
And this has to run in the fraction of a second.
However, as opposed to the bees, it can not go up, down, or even diagonal - it can only be two-dimensional, only in the direction of the reversibility of the tyres.
While there are infinitely many possibilities for the bees here to avoid other bees, the researchers were able to use only the rotating movement, or acceleration and degradation at the car robot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer lifetime than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it was about the instinctive, intelligent reaction, and less about the processing of the data, and even less about the ability to store it.
This device only has to process some inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It does not have to save them, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction by means of previous manoeuvres, so that it constantly only uses a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision prevention technology, which according to Nissan will be in production in the next ten years.
A further application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately directing the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the goal.
