"A city without cinoes is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture of the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening at the moment in the large urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multihall complex in the periphery, means long-term death for the cinema in the centre. A process that does not only appear irrevocable and irrevocable, but also bears the trains of a cultural crime.
Most of the people affected are historical places full of memories, "it is like losing a friend with which one has laid a piece of road full of emotions," said the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso," who brought him the Oskar and the great price of Cannes 20 years ago. It is the history of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a well-lost cinema for ever.
The figures provided by Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas has had to close; this tune paid for most of the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are Emilia Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This demonstrates that the main guilty are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: 195 in the last 5 years the Lombardy has introduced the lists, 81 are both in Tuscany and in Emilia Romagna.
"The business has evolved in an irrational way," said Paolo Protti, the president of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures are also emerging, but in the first place is the preservation of the already existing, because closing a hall in the city, not all his stem customers are willing to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here there is still the lack of budget for the fund of the trade union of eight: the debt burden recorded by the State is about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not respect existing laws.
In order to preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros would be needed in the year. "
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which has decided to protect them by an agreement between the municipality and the Anec because of the fears of the old cinemas; it is the first agreement of this kind in Italy, which aims to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
The measures envisaged include tax advantages for cinematographic operators as well as benefits for the public with regard to urban transport: it will be possible to travel to the transport restricted areas of the centre and also to park at cheaper parking charges.
"It is a pleasant initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and also develop new concepts.
Of course, we also need better audio and video equipment to be able to adjust to the superpower of the multiplex, because, finally, the audience of today is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been an important subject to me: closing the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the crucial point that made me start the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso," even though I had played with the thought for 10 years.
For 25 years I have lived in Rome; when I pass by the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside in order not to have to see the dust-covered posters.
